ote> <p><b> <u>sen. (candidate last) is pushing for a massive new energy tax:</u> </b> </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last)'s legislation would dramatically raise taxes on all carbon-based fuels.</b> "what is not widely understood is that he is currently sponsoring legislation that, in the name of fighting global warming, would dramatically raise the tax on all carbon-based fuels, including gasoline, home heating oil, coal, and to a lesser extent, natural gas." (roy cordato, "(candidate last)'s costly tax on energy," <em>national review</em>, www.nationalreview.com, posted 1/10/08) </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last)'s energy policy could devastate the auto industry.</b> "higher energy costs will, among other things, raise the cost of manufacturing big-ticket items in american factories. and higher gas prices will likely raise demand for those classes of automobiles that tend to be manufactured overseas. somehow, i think michigan voters will be less than thrilled about this, should anyone bother to inform them." (roy cordato, "(candidate last)'s costly tax on energy," <em>national review</em>, www.nationalreview.com, posted 1/10/08) </p><p><b> <u>sen. (candidate last)'s plan would send gas taxes sky high and would harm the national economy:</u> </b> </p><p><b>the epa estimates sen. (candidate last)'s plan would hike gas taxes by 68 cents per gallon.</b> "the epa has estimated what the (candidate last) energy tax would mean to consumers. since the bill's provisions are phased in, the full cost of the tax would not be felt for a number of years. but in a letter to senator (candidate last) dated july 2007, the epa estimated that the tax will be about $.26 cents in current dollars per gallon of gasoline by 2030 and $.68 cents per gallon by 2050." (roy cordato, "(candidate last)'s costly tax on energy," <em>national review</em>, www.nationalreview.com, posted 1/10/08) </p><p><b>the epa estimates sen. (candidate last)'s plan would reduce united states gdp by as much as $5.2 trillion.</b> "the effect on the economy of the (candidate last) tax would be similar to any other broad-based tax. in the epa's own words: 'the present value of the cumulative reduction in real gdp for the 2012-2030 period ranges from $660 billion to $2.1 trillion...the cumulative reduction in the present value of real gdp for the 2012-2050 period ranges from about $1.6 trillion to $5.2 trillion.'" (roy cordato, "(candidate last)'s costly tax on energy," <em>national review</em>, www.nationalreview.com, posted 1/10/08)</p></span>



